      "side": 1,
      "message": "d.update(field\u003d\"value\")       # doesn\u0027t work\nd.update({\"field\": \"value\"})  # works\n\n(I\u0027m not sure what you mean by `d.update(messageType(field\u003d\"value\"))`)\n\n\u003e I kind of suspect that key as a string is overwhelmingly common\n\nThey are overwhelmingly common when dicts are using as poor man\u0027s structs:\n\n   d \u003d dict(param1\u003d123, param2\u003d245)\n\nFor this case, there are starlark structs.\n\nWhen inside protos, dicts are {key \u003d\u003e value} mappings. It is possible keys are strings:\n\nmessage M {\n  map\u003cstring, int32\u003e bananas \u003d 1;\n}\n\nThe following syntax is thus proclaimed as not supported (by me, in this CL) because it is abusive and misleading:\n\n  m \u003d M()\n  m.bananas(banana1\u003d123, banana2\u003d456)\n\nInstead either use \n\n  m.bananas.update({\u0027banana1\u0027: 123, \u0027banana2\u0027: 456})\n\nOr declare \u0027bananas\u0027 as a message, with fields:\n\nmessage M {\n  message Bananas {\n    int32 banana1 \u003d 1;\n    int32 banana2 \u003d 2;\n  }\n  Bananas bananas \u003d 1;\n}\n\nm.bananas \u003d M.Bananas(banana1\u003d123, banana2\u003d456)\n\nOr, if you really want to,\n\nm.bananas.update(dict(banana1\u003d123, banana2\u003d456))",
      "parentUuid": "03a43ce0_9c557319",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 36,
        "startChar": 22,
        "endLine": 37,
        "endChar": 49
      },
